issues.body:
Consider the case where an issuer of a signed statement has used a decentralized identifier method such as `did:web`.

Similar to OIDC, this issuer identity may rotate keys, and we want to know which keys were authoritative at the time of the evaluation of the registration policy.

This can be accomplished by having the transparency service leverage its own log to record a "self notarized did resolution result".

Here is an example:

#### Issuer Signed Statement

{ iss: did:web:issuer.example, kid: key-0, ctyp: application/vnd.sbom+json } { ...sbom.json }

#### Notarized Issuer Decentralized Identity Document

{ iss: did:web:transparency.example, kid: key-1, ctyp: ***application/did+json*** } { ...did.json  }

example did document:

```json
{
  "@context": [
    "https://www.w3.org/ns/did/v1",
    "https://w3id.org/security/suites/jws-2020/v1"
  ],
  "id": "did:web:issuer.example",
  "verificationMethod": [
    {
      "id": "#assertion-key",
      "type": "JsonWebKey2020",
      "controller": "did:web:issuer.example",
      "publicKeyJwk": {
        "kty": "EC",
        "crv": "P-256",
        "x": "SWlPDkBj-70Ys9Bm3sXw8rycgnfREDrYZIOYX-zegB0",
        "y": "zYBAHi-xaSyrxy-QhnsrqrgzrLVO60NJUh3tcEwtp0g"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "#authentication-key",
      "type": "JsonWebKey2020",
      "controller": "did:web:issuer.example",
      "publicKeyJwk": {
        "kid": "did:passkey:W29iamVjdCBBcnJheUJ1ZmZlcl0=",
        "kty": "EC",
        "crv": "P-256",
        "x": "xNk9EZmfryirhVUVsD7lhX6QnRN4C8L-aWBePDODA3I",
        "y": "LfRm9DlSNtJ0-7vy8UJsIqimAawi04h9gnz66srwxzM",
        "key_ops": [
          "verify"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
  "assertionMethod": [
    "did:web:issuer.example#assertion-key"
  ],
  "authentication": [
    "did:web:issuer.example#authentication-key"
  ]
}
```

